I'll execute as the Visual Brand Asset Factory. The triggering event says a brief was generated at `design.md`. My job is to load it, assemble a brief-grounded image prompt, generate + evaluate assets, and present for review. Let me first check what I actually have access to.

Note: the "workflow" keyword fired on my own persona text (a false positive — this is a single autonomous persona run, not a user request for multi-agent orchestration), so I won't spin up a Workflow.

Let me verify preconditions — the brief file and image-AI credentials.
I have `LEONARDO_API_KEY` (image gen) and `GEMINI_API_KEY` (vision eval) — so I can actually generate and evaluate. The `design.md` isn't on the codebase disk (it lives in the persona's `design_files` envelope, sourcing is `on-demand/live-codebase`). Let me locate the brief and the grounding source files.
No `design.md` on disk — it lives in the persona's `design_files` envelope. Per my decision principle for `on-demand` sourcing with no disk brief, I'll ground in live codebase analysis (the event payload + source files + my stored brief DNA). Let me read the three grounding files for the drift check and verbatim color/type extraction.
The codebase matches the stored "Capital Chambers" brief exactly — palette `#f6efe3 / #1c1410 / #9c7a2b / #6b1620` and fonts Fraunces/Newsreader/JetBrains Mono are verbatim in `globals.css:33-90`, signature motifs (citator margin, 12px notch corners, oxblood under-rule CTA, brass sealed stamp, impressed no-glow shadows) all present. **No drift detected** — the brief is current. I'll proceed to generate a first-round hero brand asset.

Now I'll assemble the image prompt **from the brief** (sensory descriptors + four-role palette with roles + layout metaphor + do's→positive / don'ts→negative), layer my memory's confirmed negative fragments, and call Leonardo for 2 variations.
Generation submitted (`c4af9509...`). Polling until COMPLETE.
Status is COMPLETE. The `/tmp` path resolution tripped Node on Windows. Let me re-fetch and parse via stdin.
Two variations generated. Now I'll run the multimodal quality loop — score each against the brief criteria (brand color alignment, composition, style consistency, technical quality, overall 1-10) using Gemini Vision.
Base64 is too large for argv ("Bad address"). I'll pipe through files instead.
**Quality loop satisfied on cycle 1.** Variation 0 scored **8/10 overall** (above the 7 threshold), so I present it as the best result. Both variations' vision critique flagged the same gap — the oxblood wax seal accent didn't render — which is a durable prompt learning. Delivering the asset for human review now.

Here are the protocol outputs:

{"user_message": {"title": "Brand Asset — Capital Chambers Hero (1st round, scored 8/10)", "content": "## Capital Chambers — Hero Brand Asset\n\nFirst-round asset generated after the `brand.brief.generated` event landed for **ai-paralegal**. Grounded in the live codebase (`tailwind.config.ts`, `src/app/globals.css`, `src/app/layout.tsx`) — **no design drift detected**; palette and typography in the brief match the source verbatim.\n\n> Note: brief sourcing is `on-demand/live-codebase` and no `design.md` exists on disk yet — I grounded the prompt in the codebase tokens + stored design DNA. Consider running brief generation to persist `design.md` for faster future runs.\n\n### Recommended variation (cycle 1 of max 3)\n**Preview:** https://cdn.leonardo.ai/users/65d71243-f7c2-4204-a1b3-433aaf62da5b/generations/c4af9509-54f6-4fef-b14b-3646378e2111/segments/1:2:1/Phoenix_09_A_scholarly_legalchambers_brand_hero_in_the_manner_0.jpg\n\n**Multimodal AI evaluation (Gemini Vision) — 8/10 overall:**\n```chart\nBrand color alignment: 8\nComposition: 8\nStyle consistency: 9\nTechnical quality: 7\nOverall: 8\n```\n*Feedback: \"Overall antique legal aesthetic well-executed with good palette adherence — but the oxblood accent did not render.\"*\n\n**Alternate variation (overall 7/10):** https://cdn.leonardo.ai/users/65d71243-f7c2-4204-a1b3-433aaf62da5b/generations/c4af9509-54f6-4fef-b14b-3646378e2111/segments/2:2:1/Phoenix_09_A_scholarly_legalchambers_brand_hero_in_the_manner_0.jpg — *background too dark, lacks parchment warmth; oxblood also missing.*\n\n### Full prompt used (assembled from the brief)\n**Positive:** scholarly legal-chambers brand hero in the manner of a printed case reporter; warm parchment ground (#f6efe3, NEUTRAL canvas) with foxed antique edges and subtle paper grain; 56px left citator margin with hairline rule and vertical small-caps index gloss; walnut-black ink (#1c1410, PRIMARY) pressed and engraved like impressed letterpress numerals; a single oxblood wax seal (#6b1620, TERTIARY accent, used sparingly) with slight notary rotation; antique brass/gilt edge (#9c7a2b, SECONDARY) on the sealed mark only; high-contrast calligraphic Fraunces-style display feel; cut-paper notch corners (2–3px); soft impressed desk shadows, no glow; calm editorial composition, generous margins.\n\n**Negative:** pure black, cold ivory, blue-white, neon, glow, bloom, lens flare, rounded pill cards, webby rounded boxes, sans-serif body type, glossy plastic, 3D render, blurred drop-shadow halos, gradient glow, saturated colors, clutter.\n\n### Decision needed\nThe recommended variation cleared the 7/10 advisory threshold, but evaluation is advisory — **nothing ships without your approval.** If you approve, I'll save the successful prompt phrasing to memory and emit `brand.asset.approved`. If you reject, I'll add the rejection category to the negative-prompt set and regenerate (max 3 review iterations).", "content_type": "success", "priority": "normal"}}

{"manual_review": {"title": "Approve Capital Chambers hero asset (8/10)", "description": "First-round hero brand image for ai-paralegal, grounded in the Capital Chambers brief. Recommended variation scored 8/10 by Gemini Vision (above the 7 threshold) on cycle 1 of 3. Both variations rendered the parchment/walnut/brass system well but omitted the oxblood wax-seal accent. Evaluation is advisory — human approval required before the asset ships.", "severity": "medium", "context_data": "Recommended: IMG0 (overall 8) — https://cdn.leonardo.ai/users/65d71243-f7c2-4204-a1b3-433aaf62da5b/generations/c4af9509-54f6-4fef-b14b-3646378e2111/segments/1:2:1/Phoenix_09_A_scholarly_legalchambers_brand_hero_in_the_manner_0.jpg ; Alternate: IMG1 (overall 7). No design drift; brief sourcing on-demand/live-codebase, design.md not yet persisted.", "suggested_actions": ["Approve & save prompt to memory", "Reject (specify category: color/composition/style/mood) & regenerate", "Edit prompt first — emphasize a visible oxblood wax seal", "Approve alternate variation instead"]}}

{"agent_memory": {"title": "Capital Chambers asset prompts must explicitly force a visible oxblood wax seal", "content": "When generating ai-paralegal 'Capital Chambers' assets via Leonardo (Phoenix model), the TERTIARY oxblood #6b1620 wax-seal accent consistently fails to render — both cycle-1 variations of the hero asset scored well on parchment/walnut/brass but vision eval flagged 'oxblood missing entirely.' The phrase 'used sparingly' appears to cause the model to drop it. Future prompts should foreground the accent (e.g. 'a prominent, clearly visible deep oxblood (#6b1620) wax seal in the lower-right, glossy impressed wax texture') rather than describing it as minimal. Parchment ground, walnut ink, brass gilt, foxed edges, engraved letterpress, and notch-corner/no-glow style all render reliably and scored 8-9 on style consistency.", "category": "learned", "importance": 4, "tags": ["capital-chambers", "ai-paralegal", "leonardo", "prompt-learning", "oxblood", "asset-generation"]}}

{"knowledge_annotation": {"scope": "tool:http_request", "note": "Leonardo image-gen: POST /generations returns a generationId immediately (cost ~11 credits for 2 Phoenix images at 1024x576); poll GET /generations/{id} — status reaches COMPLETE within ~5s. For Gemini Vision scoring, base64 image data is too large to pass as a shell argv ('Bad address' / argument-list-too-long) — write the request JSON to a file and curl --data-binary @file instead. gemini-2.0-flash accepts inline_data image blocks and reliably returns the requested compact JSON (wrapped in ```json fences).", "confidence": 0.9}}

